result.execSummary:
The defendant Meagan L. Jagiello was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/ Intent/Deliver Prescriptions [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 450.11(7)(g).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Meagan L. Jagiello in court with attorney Patrick Howard Finlan.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 11:05 AM. State - resolved. Finlan - provided court with plea questionnaire with attachments - plead G/NC to count #2 as alleged, remaining counts are to be dismissed and read in, withhold sentence and place on probation for 3 years with conditions of: 90 days jail, 200 hours of community service as deemed appropriate by P&P, AODA and follow thru, court costs, DNA sample and surcharge, State will not file additional bail jumping, defense is free to argue jail time. Jagiello agrees and understands. Court dismisses and reads in counts #1, #3 and #4. Jagiello pleads G to count #2 as alleged. Court has plea questionnaire, goes thru it, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived her constitutional rights by entering her plea and right to JT, accepts plea, adjudges guilty, proceed to sentencing. State makes final argument prior to sentencing - recommends 90 days jail plus other conditions as stated by Finlan. Finlan does object to statements made by the State in his sentencing argument. State responds, it is part of the criminal complaint. Court notes objection, makes no ruling. Finlan makes final argument prior to sentencing - 27 days credit (stipulated) - argues against conditional jail. Jagiello makes statement. Court sentences the defendant to the following: count #2 - withhold sentence and place on probaton for 3 years with conditions of: AODA and follow thru, costs - take bond posted, submit DNA sample, 30 days in FC jail - huber allowed - 27 days credit only if revoked - eligible for community service under 973.09(7m) - no objections to serving the sentence in another county but it is the ultimate decision of the Sheriff(s) - report by 3:00 PM on 11/25/16, 200 hours of community service - to be completed within the first 2 years of probation, no voting rights, no possession of firearms, right to appeal. Finlan asks for the Court to waive the fees of the DNA sample. Court - not waiving the costs. Adjourned.
Status conference on October 19, 2016 at 08:30 am.

Defendant Meagan L. Jagiello in court with attorney Patrick Howard Finlan appearing by telephone.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called 2:39 PM. Finlan has filed motion to withdraw due to break down in communication. Jagiello makes statement that she was sentenced in Milwaukee County and had to serve time at the time she had an appointment with Finlan. State indicates there was an offer. Finlan had consulted with Jagiello and unsure if she want to take this to trial. Jagiello willing to work with Finlan. Finlan unsure if he can represent her due to communication issues. Court does not grant motion for stated reasons and instructs Jagiello to call Finlan immediately, if agreement is reached a PLEAS can be scheduled. State asks if agreement is made that a PLEAS be scheduled on or before 10/19/16.  Status conference scheduled for October 19, 2016 at 08:30 am.
Motion hearing on October 10, 2016 at 02:30 pm.

Defendant Meagan L. Jagiello in court with attorney Patrick Howard Finlan.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 4:38 PM. Defendant Meagan L. Jagiello in court with attorney Patrick Howard Finlan.  Defendant Meagan L. Jagiello in custody (for Outagamie County).  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Called at 3:42 PM. Here for motion to suppress that was recently filed but State thought it was a FPT hearing today. Court asks questions in regard to motion filed. Finlan explains motion. State responds - not prepared for motion due to recent illness. Finlan wants the phone in the courtroom and that has been stated in the motion. Court continues bond at this point, sets for another MH.  Motion hearing scheduled for March 28, 2016 at 10:00 am.

Defendant Meagan L. Jagiello in court with attorney Patrick Howard Finlan.  Charles James Simono appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Also called 15CF143. Ernest Long appears in person and in custody with attorney Burns. Finlan - his client would waive PH today if he's allowed to ask questions during Long's PH. State has no objections. Court will allow. Jagiello will waive PH for today. Court goes thru verbal collaquey of waiver of PH, finds the defendant has freely, voluntarily and intelligenlty waived her right to PH, finds probable cause, binds over for trial. State files Information that mirrors the complaint. State calls Detective Sgt. Steve Ashbeck. Ashbeck sworn in at 3:28 PM. Direct exam by State.  Finlan objects - overruled (3:32 PM). Record reflects proper identification of defendant Long (3:39 PM). Cross exam by Burns at 3:44 PM. State objects - asked and answered - overruled (3:47 PM). Cross exam by Finlan at 3:49 PM. State objects to portion of the question - overruled (3:50 PM). State objects - asked and answered - overruled (3:50 PM). State objects - overruled (3:51 PM). Re-direct by State at 3:52 PM. Ashbeck excused at 3:52 PM. Burns makes argument for Court to not find probable cause. State responds - disagrees - asks that both defendants be bound over. Burns makes another statement. Court - finds probable cause that each defendant may have committed a felony, binds both defendants over for court. State files Information that mirrors complaint for Long. Finlan waives reading of Information, will proceed to ARGN, enters NG pleas to all counts. Burns waives reading of Information, will proceed to ARGN, enters NG pleas to all counts. Court continues bond on both defendants, sets both cases for FPT.  Final pre-trial scheduled for March 9, 2016 at 01:45 pm.
